s of a landslide (PA Wire)Mr Sunak addressed the crowds after Mr Johnson, hailing the ‚Äúunited Conservative family‚Äù and claiming just 130,000 voters could help stem his party‚Äôs predicted losses.Speaking at the rally the Prime Minister said: ‚ÄúIsn‚Äôt it great to have our Conservative family united, my friends?‚ÄùMr Sunak added: ‚ÄúNow, it suits lots of people to say that the result of this election is a foregone conclusion but I know that it is not.‚ÄúJust 130,000 people switching their vote, giving us their support, is what it will take to deny Labour that supermajority they want. Every single vote matters.‚ÄùEarlier on Tuesday, Sir Keir Starmer refused to entertain suggestions he will lead his party to a landslide victory at one of his final visits.He told campaigners: ‚ÄúPeople are saying the polls predict the future ‚Äì they don‚Äôt predict the future, every single vote counts, every single vote has to be earned and in places like this it‚Äôll probably go down to a few hundred either way and therefore the worst thing for people who want change is to think ‚Äòjob done‚Äô and ‚Äòwe don‚Äôt need to vote because there‚Äôs going to be a majority in any event‚Äô.‚ÄúIt isn‚Äôt ‚Äòjob done‚Äô.‚ÄùSir Keir, who is set to visit England, Wales and Scotland on the final day of campaigning, added: ‚ÄúGiven that the country is pretty broken at the moment, a lot of things aren‚Äôt working, there‚Äôs a big job for us to do if we come in to serve and we need a strong mandate for that.‚ÄúWe need to know the country genuinely wants this change and that we‚Äôre sort of all prepared to say this is the change that we want and it gives a real strong mandate to a government to say ‚Äòwe‚Äôve asked you to change things, you need to get on with it‚Äô.‚Äù"
